        "title": "Tribal officers — covenant land under covenant accountability",
        "range": "27:16-22",
        "excerpt": "Now in charge of the tribes of Israel … these were the princes of the tribes of Israel",
        "body": "The tribal officer list (27:16-22) is the chapter's most compact roster and its most theologically conservative. Where the military divisions reflect innovation — the rotating-division system is David's administrative creation — the tribal officer structure reflects antiquity: Israel has always been organized by tribes. David's genius is not to replace the tribal framework but to name accountable officers within it.\n\nThe roster is notable for two inclusions and two apparent omissions. Aaron is listed separately from Levi (27:17) — Zadok represents the Aaronic priesthood while Hashabiah represents the broader Levitical tribe. This is consistent with the Chronicler's sustained attention to the Zadokite priesthood throughout 1 Chronicles 23-26. The two omissions — Gad and Asher — have generated significant discussion among commentators. H.G.M. Williamson (*1 and 2 Chronicles*, New Century Bible, 1982) suggests textual disruption; Sara Japhet (*I & II Chronicles*, Old Testament Library, 1993) accepts the list as intentionally representative rather than exhaustive, noting that 'twelve tribes' in Israel was never a fixed configuration. The Chronicler's point is preserved regardless: every tribe that appears has a named, accountable officer before the king.\n\nThe inclusion of both halves of Manasseh — western Manasseh (27:20) and Manasseh in Gilead (27:21) — is geographically significant. The kingdom extends east of the Jordan. The covenant land in its full extent, from Gilead to the coastal plain, is under ordered administration. For post-exilic readers whose territory was a fraction of that, this roster functioned as a map of the promise not yet fully recovered.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Shevet* (tribe) means literally a rod or staff — the tribal identity is linked to the imagery of rulership and shepherd authority. The tribes are not merely ethnic groupings but covenant-administrative units. *Sar* (prince, officer, commander) is the same word used in 27:1 for military commanders — the term blurs the line between military and civil authority, suggesting that all governance in Israel is a form of commanded service under the king."
