        "body": "The estate roster is, on its surface, the most prosaic section of the chapter — nine names, nine commodities, nine stewardship domains. But the Chronicler's inclusion of this level of detail is itself an argument. Every resource that flows from Israel's land — grain, wine, oil, livestock of every kind — is administered by a named and accountable steward. Nothing is ambient. Nothing is unowned. The phrase that closes the section makes the point explicit: 'all these were overseers of the property which belonged to King David' (27:31). Every steward is accountable to the king; the king is accountable to the LORD whose land it ultimately is (Leviticus 25:23).\n\nThe geographic range of the stewardship is worth mapping: storehouses in the cities, villages, and towers (27:25), field workers on the soil (27:26), vineyards at Ramah (27:27), wine cellars (27:27), olive and sycamore orchards in the Shephelah (27:28), oil stores (27:28), cattle on the coastal plain of Sharon (27:29), cattle in the hill-country valleys (27:29), camels (27:30), donkeys (27:30), flocks (27:31). The range is from coastal plain to highland valley, from grain field to orchard, from pack animals to pasture herds. The entire material economy of the kingdom is named and stewarded.\n\nFor the Chronicler's post-exilic audience — a community returning to a land whose agricultural infrastructure had been devastated by Babylonian invasion and decades of neglect — this roster is not merely history. It is a picture of what restored administration could look like. Every domain of the land's produce can be stewarded rightly. The land itself, given back by God after exile, is again to be held accountable before the King.\n\nTwo estate officers merit particular notice. Baal-hanan the Gederite (27:28) has a theophoric name containing *Baal* — a Canaanite divine name. His presence in David's court without comment illustrates the complexity of Israelite administrative life; the Chronicler's silence is not endorsement of Baal worship but a realistic record of the kingdom's personnel. Obil the Ishmaelite (27:30) — named for Ishmael, Abraham's son by Hagar — oversees the camels. David's administration includes non-Israelites in positions of legitimate stewardship, reflecting the breadth of the Abrahamic promise that the nations would be blessed through Abraham's seed (Genesis 12:3)."
