        "body": "The chapter's final three verses name five men in four roles: counselor-scribe (Jonathan, 27:32), royal tutor (Jehiel, 27:32), counselor (Ahithophel, 27:33), king's friend (Hushai, 27:33), and army commander (Joab, 27:34). The brevity of the section belies the density of its backstory. Every reader of 2 Samuel knows that Ahithophel defected to Absalom during the rebellion, gave counsel that 2 Samuel 16:23 compares to the word of God, saw his counsel defeated by Hushai's counter-advice, and hanged himself (2 Samuel 17:23). Hushai was the loyal counter-agent David sent back into Jerusalem specifically to 'defeat the counsel of Ahithophel' (2 Samuel 15:34).\n\nThe Chronicler places Ahithophel and Hushai in the same administrative list without editorial comment. This restraint is itself interpretively significant. The Chronicler is not rewriting David's history to remove its failures; he is presenting the court as it was — including its treacheries and loyalties. The advisory council that sustained David's kingdom included a man who would betray him. The 'king's friend' who kept the counsel honest was not the official counselor but the relational companion. The lesson for governance is not that officeholders are reliable and friends are not, but that no institutional arrangement guarantees the character of the men who fill it.\n\nJoab closes the list as army commander (27:34) — the same Joab whose unauthorized census brought wrath (27:24). The Chronicler ends his entire five-chapter administrative survey with this name. The effect is chastening. The most ordered kingdom in Israel's history — Levites in rotation, priests assigned, singers in their divisions, gatekeepers at their posts, military forces in monthly rotation, tribal officers in place, estate stewards covering every commodity, wise counselors attending the king — still contained Joab. Structure is indispensable. Character is irreplaceable.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Rea* (friend, 27:33) — Hushai the king's *friend* is a technical term in ancient Near Eastern royal administration: the *rea'* was a recognized court position involving personal intimacy and access. In Egypt it was translated as 'sole companion of the king.' Hushai's loyalty in the Absalom crisis (2 Samuel 15-17) was the loyalty of this particular role. *Yaats* (counselor) appears in both 27:32 and 27:33 — the Chronicler's repetition of the term for both Jonathan and Ahithophel invites comparison: Jonathan is qualified as 'a man of understanding'; Ahithophel is named without such qualification."
